Q: Parsing colons using macros in C++ without needing to write a parser DSL A: <p>Macros are the wrong approach. If you want a DSL, then you want your C++ app to be an interpreter of the DSL, not contain the DSL code itself.</p>
<p>You are right to avoid a full parser and AST for such a trivial DSL--you can more easily parse it with regex or read input character by character, then map the resulting data to the <code>Book</code> constructor.</p>
<pre class="lang-cpp prettyprint-override"><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;fstream&gt;
#include &lt;string&gt;
#include &lt;regex&gt;
#include &lt;vector&gt;

class Book {
public:
    Book(std::string name, std::string author) 
        : name(name), author(author) {}

    std::string name;
    std::string author;
};

std::vector&lt;Book*&gt; parseBooks(const std::string&amp; filepath) {
    std::ifstream file(filepath);
    std::string content((std::istreambuf_iterator&lt;char&gt;(file)),
                        std::istreambuf_iterator&lt;char&gt;());

    std::vector&lt;Book*&gt; books;
    std::regex pattern(R&quot;(CREATE BOOK\s*\{\s*NAME:\s*&quot;([^&quot;]+)&quot;\s*,\s*AUTHOR:\s*&quot;([^&quot;]+)&quot;\s*,\s*\})&quot;);

    auto begin = std::sregex_iterator(content.begin(), content.end(), pattern);
    auto end = std::sregex_iterator();

    for (auto it = begin; it != end; ++it) {
        std::smatch match = *it;
        books.push_back(new Book(match[1].str(), match[2].str()));
    }

    return books;
}

int main() {
    // assumes the DSL code will be in a file &quot;books.dsl&quot;
    auto books = parseBooks(&quot;books.dsl&quot;);

    for (const auto&amp; book : books) {
        std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Book: &quot; &lt;&lt; book-&gt;name &lt;&lt; &quot; by &quot; &lt;&lt; book-&gt;author &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
        delete book;
    }

    return 0;
}
</code></pre>
<p>However, if you are only feeding in a list of Books (name and author), then you are much better off using a standard data file format to encode the book list. You should read a CSV or JSON file instead.</p>

Q: Is on the fly (runtime-compiled) ShaderFunction for ShaderLibrary possible? A: <p>I am researching this topic too, since dynamic compilation of metal shaders seems to be the only way to use them in Swift Playgrounds (<a href="https://developer.apple.com/forums/thread/774771" rel="nofollow noreferrer">apple forums</a>)</p>
<p>I did manage to create a reference to <code>ShaderLibrary</code> like this:</p>
<pre class="lang-swift prettyprint-override"><code>
// I am using .txt and not .metal. This is Playground specific.
// Please ignore forced unwrapping. 
let shaderURL = Bundle.main.url(forResource: &quot;shaders&quot;, withExtension: &quot;txt&quot;)!
let source = try! String(contentsOf: shaderURL, encoding: .utf8)

do {
    let device = MTLCreateSystemDefaultDevice()!    
    let opt = MTLCompileOptions()
    opt.enableLogging = true
    // Those two options are important.
    opt.libraryType = .dynamic
    opt.installName = &quot;shaders.metallib&quot;

    // We need to create MTLLibrary...
    let library = try device.makeLibrary(source: source, options: opt)
    // ...that we convert into dynamic library...
    let dynLib = try device.makeDynamicLibrary(library: library)

    // ...that we can serialize to disk as metallib file...
    let tempUrl : URL = .temporaryDirectory.appending(
        component: dynLib.installName, directoryHint: .notDirectory)
    try dynLib.serialize(to: tempUrl)

    // ... that we can finally read as ShaderLibrary
    let sLib = ShaderLibrary(url: tempUrl)
} catch {
    // 
}
</code></pre>
<p>Problem is, it does not work when used in say <code>.colorEffect</code> - everything just hangs, and as I am using Playgrounds, debugging anything is impossible.</p>
<p>I thought I will share and will update this answer when I make some progress. Maybe it will help you figure something out.</p>
<p>Cheers,<br />
Dawid</p>
